    </connection>
    <connection>
      <id>1</id>
      <facing>6</facing>
      <connectionname>Relay Up</connectionname>
      <type>1</type>
      <consumer>True</consumer>
      <audiosource>False</audiosource>
      <videosource>False</videosource>
      <linelevel>False</linelevel>
      <classes>
        <class>
          <classname>RELAY</classname>
        </class>
      </classes>
    </connection>
    <connection>
      <id>2</id>
      <facing>6</facing>
      <connectionname>Relay Down</connectionname>
      <type>1</type>
      <consumer>True</consumer>
      <audiosource>False</audiosource>
      <videosource>False</videosource>
      <linelevel>False</linelevel>
      <classes>
        <class>
          <classname>RELAY</classname>
        </class>
      </classes>
    </connection>
  </connections><config><documentation>
In conjunction with the Card Access Wireless Relay hardware, this driver provides the ability to simultaneously pulse both the "up" and "down" control lines of a shade motor to signal a stop command. The driver also supports pulsing either control line alone to effect a stop.

Pulse Length: Time is in milliseconds (1/2 second = 0.5 second = 500 milliseconds). Minimum is 60 ms; maximum is 5000 ms. A pulse that is too short may not be reliably detected by the shade motor; a pulse that is too long may cause the motor to begin moving but then stop when the pulse ends. Refer to motor documentation.

Travel Up time, Travel Down time: Enter the amount of time required for the shade to travel full-length between the fully open and fully closed positions. Minimum time is 1 second; maximum is 120 seconds.

Stop method: Choose how to signal the "stop" command to the shade motor:
      pulse both relays together
      always pulse the last direction relay (if the last command was up then pulse up again to stop; if the last command was down then pulse down again to stop)
      always pulse only the UP relay
      always pulse only the DOWN relay

Events:
      Starts going Up: happens when "Up" command is sent
      Starts going Down: happens when "Down" command is sent
      Stops: happens ONLY when "Stop" command is sent -- the driver does not attempt to estimate when the shade will stop after an Up/Down/Toggle command. Write a script on the "Starts going Up/Down" event(s) and use a Delay instruction if you want this behavior.

  </documentation><properties>
    <property>
      <name>Pulse Length (milliseconds)</name>
      <type>STRING</type>
      <default>500</default>
      <readonly>false</readonly>
    </property>
    <property>
      <name>Travel Up time (seconds)</name>
      <type>STRING</type>
      <default>5</default>
      <readonly>false</readonly>
    </property>
    <property>
      <name>Travel Down time (seconds)</name>
      <type>STRING</type>
      <default>5</default>
      <readonly>false</readonly>
    </property>
    <property>
      <name>Stop method</name>
      <type>LIST</type>
      <items>
        <item>Pulse both relays together</item>
        <item>Pulse the LAST DIRECTION relay</item>
        <item>Pulse the UP relay</item>
        <item>Pulse the DOWN relay</item>
      </items>
      <default>Pulse both relays together</default>
      <readonly>false</readonly>
    </property>
    <property>
      <name>Debug Mode</name>
      <type>LIST</type>
      <items>
        <item>Off</item>
        <item>Print</item>
        <item>Log</item>
        <item>Print and Log</item>
      </items>
      <default>Off</default>
      <readonly>false</readonly>
    </property>
  </properties><script encryption="1">
